If you want to succeed in chemistry, change your frame of mind from thinking of 'formulas' to thinking of 'deductions' - e.g., *how* do I logically get from quantity A to quantity B. For example, in this case, you know you want to convert from a quantity of one reactant to another - that's what the (balanced) chemical formula is for, relating mols to mols. But, you have grams instead - use the periodic table to find molar mass; or in this case, they've simply given it to you.

>>1283156
I am guessing your instructor has covered dimensional analysis? I will write out the full 'relation' for the problem here, in terms of units.

(g P4 / 1) * (mol P4 / g P4) * (mol O2 / mol P4) * (g O2 / mol O2) = g O2

As you can see, the units will all cancel, leaving with you with some quantity of grams. As for the numerator and denominator of these ratios, they are simple to calculate beforehand, so long as you are careful about placing 'which' scalar 'where' - hence, the units. Naively multiplying without respect for units is a recipe for failure.
